Whilst the UI might seem intimidating at first it's actually very intuitive. Press and hold on any element to get help text. Once you get to grips with it you'll realise that it's enormously powerful and a lot of fun. You have 4 sound engines: pulsewidth, FM, noise and sampler. The sampler allows you to record your own sounds through the microphone or load WAVs. Once you've got some quality loops you can put them into the tracker to create your song, it's so much quicker than a traditional arrangement view. There's loads of nice touches like pattern shift and pattern length which allow you to easily create variations and polyrhythms. I spent an entire 2.5 hour plane journey jamming on this app. Highly recommended.

Pretty good on-the-go sound editing sampler sequencer type deal. Slight learning curve but not that bad. Bit glitchy occasionally but nothing serious just UI buggy numbers when changing pitch but you just let go the button and it's good to go again. Very workable, nice tool. Dig it.

replyContent:
In a sampler instrument (g and h by default), tap the 3rd icon from the right above the sample to reveal a menu with load, save, copy and paste. "load" opens a list with files in Nanoloop/Samples (empty by default) in internal memory.
To import samples, connect your phone to a PC and move samples or entire folders to said folder.
WAV only, no mp3.

This app is unbeatable. For those catching up, this is a game boy music app ported to the cell phone and works even better than the original. "Note length" on samples acts as a form of velocity control which provides lots of variance in a written beat. This has all the options and none of the problems of shoddy music software commonly found on phones. Like another guy said, if you can't figure out how to make good music with this app then consider something else to fill your time.
My favorite app of all time.
For its size and simplicity this thing rocks!
Perfect tiny music app
Like a return to speak and Spell with an alchemical finesse. Simply impressive
Finalmente funciona no Motorola Spice (XT300)!

The most versatile music based app I've ever used. Nanoloop is engaging and rewarding from the start - continuing to offer more functionality through use, and through regular updates. Best Android purchase I have ever made.
Beautifully designed and sounding app

I've been a fan of nanoloop from the GB days, and am stoked to have it on my phone now. But I wish there were a few tweaks with file navigation... 1) what's the deal with the case sensitive alphabetization? Very inconvenient. and 2) any chance of implementing a double-tap or long-press to immediately select a file or navigate to a folder?  Update: fantastic! An unexpected update on a very mature program 11/27/13.
Enjoyed the performance capabilities. Still one of the best music-making apps for Android.
It definitely has a learning curve but it's great once you experiment with it and figure it out, bit by bit lol. The interface is just amazing, I love it.
The new update has made it easier to use, and less confusing and its a lot of fun to play around with.

This user interface should be in the design museum. It's a bit hipster but you can adjust the volume, attack, decay, LFO depth and speed (doubles as filter envelope), cutoff frequency and pulse width OF EACH INDIVIDUAL NOTE from the step sequencer screen.  Excellent for making chip music but also has a sampler. If you can't make good music on this you should think about doing something else with your time.

I've been a long time user of nanoloop now and have enjoyed the features on the touch version, although the recent update has made the interface a little too cluttered for me and I'm finding it very hard to make anything on it anymore which is a shame. I'd love a 'classic mode' if it was possible. The nice pixel font has been replaced now by a boring default. Can't find any proper manual on the new features either... Feeling a little left in the dark here! Don't let my criticism put a new user off though.
replyContent:
There will be a full manual soon. However, the new version should be mostly self-explaining (keep icons touched for info).     
The pixel font is still there for the interface, only in places with longer text (file names, menu), the system font is used.     
Finally, if you have a question, there is always asupport@nanoloop.com.

content: The update looks nice and the app is usually perfect but now it crashes instantly every single time. Needs another update! Samsung Galaxy s2.
replyContent: PLEASE contact asupport@nanoloop.com, I need more info to help you. Possibly just an incomplete install. Please try to uninstall and re-install via Play Store first. Thank you.

content: Well worth paying for. Update Dec 2013: the recent update surprised me, amazing, well thought out additions. thank you!

Love this little program
Oliver, you are a genius ;) Great app, the new update it was a surprise....Chiptune rules ~ * / \ Â¥
Best Android audio app, hands down. Blows all competition out of the water.
I've tried caustic, SV, groovebox, and none of them can dish out what nanoloop has to offer. Thanks dev for the new update blew my mind.

Dev has really been working hard to make this one of the coolest beat-  / groove-making tools and beyond available on the platform. I can't believe how much he's added in the last year alone. The latest update, with varying pattern lengths and added per-note parameter control, is ABSOLUTELY KILLER. Obvious application is making basic EDM and hip-hop, but a creative user can definitely get much more out of it. Anyone complaining about the interface is just being unreasonable / ridiculous - there's a SLIGHT learning curve but for work on a phone-sized touchscreen sans BT keyboard etc., what Oliver has created here is as clever, usable and efficient as it gets. (I love SV too, but let's face it, making music with it is an exercise in pure masochism w/o proper keyboard AND mouse.)
Awesome update!
The coolest app I have ever bought just got better!
Probably the best (and easiest to use) music sequencer on the market for android. It had broke when I updated to kitkat 4.4, but the most recent update fixed it. Thanks, and keep up the good work! :D

Great app. So far very stable on LG Optimus S. Wish I could sample longer but there are other apps for that. Looks to be very full fledged for composing. The app Tapemachine is useful for converting ogg to mp3 or wav.

I've used this program ever since the gameboy days, amazing app best for making music ever. Display a bit funny on my.  Nexus 5 pleas update.

content: Lovely synth, best I've seen in a long while. So happy to see a program that embraces the natural limitations of its platform. Dare I call it an instrument and not a toy? Yes, I dare.

replyContent: I do respond to e-mails. I may be a little slow sometimes when it's not a support issue (this was a refund request).

Make sure you run it for 10 mins with an internet connection or its useless!
replyContent: Besides a single license check, nanoloop does NOT require an internet connection, it does not even have the permission to use internet (license check is a separate permission). The license check ist performed within 10 min when running for the first time. The result is stored locally permanently so that it can then be used completely offline.

replyContent: It would be very helpful if you could provide some details about the crashes (under which circumstances, on which device / Android version etc). Thank you.
